a) Reserving the juice, drain the @pineapple rings{1} using a #colander{}. 

b) Mix half of the @ginger puree{1/2} per person, the @soy sauce{25%ml}, @tomato ketchup{1%tbsp} and 1 tbsp of pineapple juice per person in a #small bowl{}. Stir to combine. This is your marinade.

a) Pop the @diced chicken breast{260%g} into a #medium bowl{}. 

b) Pour in half of the marinade and a drizzle of @oil{}.

Mix to coat the chicken evenly.

> TIP: Don't add all of the marinade the rest is for the coleslaw.

c) Pop the chicken onto a #foil-lined baking tray{} and grill until done, ~{12%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat! The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle!

a) Chop the pineapple rings into 1cm pieces. Trim, halve and deseed the @green chilli{1/2}. Finely chop into small pieces.

b) Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} over medium-high heat.

c) Pop the pineapple, green chilli and the rest of the @ginger puree{1/2} into the pan. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

d) Stir the @steamed basmati rice{1} into the pan and cook until piping hot, ~{2%minutes}.

> TIP: Stir occasionally to break up any lumps.

a) Zest the @lime{1} then cut into wedges. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all).

b) Pop the @coleslaw mix{120%g} into a #large bowl{}. Mix through half the coriander and the remaining marinade you reserved in Step 2.

Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

a) Once the rice is piping hot, add a good squeeze of lime juice, a pinch of lime zest and the rest of the coriander. Mix well.

b) Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

c) Remove from the heat.

a) When the chicken is cooked, serve the pineapple fried-rice on #plates{} with the chicken pieces on top.

b) Pop the Asian slaw on the side along with any remaining lime wedges. Dig in!